==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin [[hypaethrus]], from Greek [[ύπαιθρος]], from [[ύπο-]] + [[αιθηρ]] ‘air, ether’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /hʌɪ'pi:θɹəl/

===Adjective===
'''hypaethral'''
# [[open-air]], [[outdoor]], exposed to the [[sky]]
#:*'''1974''': There was a dignity in their '''hypaethral''' presence kin to summer’s first morning of taurine light in the pepper trees of Uruguay. — Guy Davenport, ''Tatlin!''

